==History of the Internet==
{{Main|History of the Internet}}

* Networks prior to the Internet
** [[NPL network]] &ndash;  a local area computer network operated by a team from the [[National Physical Laboratory (United Kingdom)|National Physical Laboratory]] in England, the first to implement [[packet switching]], the design of which influenced other networks that followed.
** [[ARPANET]] &ndash; the first wide-area packet switching network, developed by the [[Advanced Research Projects Agency]] in the United States, and one of the first networks to implement the [[TCP/IP]] protocol suite which later became a technical foundation of the Internet.
** [[SATNET]] &ndash; an early satellite packet-switched network, also developed by the Advanced Research Projects Agency, which implemented TCP/IP before the ARPANET.
** [[Merit Network]] &ndash; a computer network created in 1966 to connect the mainframe computers at universities that is currently the oldest running regional computer network in the United States.
** [[CYCLADES]] &ndash; a French research network created in the early 1970s that pioneered the concept of [[internetworking]] by making the [[Host (network)|hosts]] responsible for the reliable delivery of data on a packet-switched network, rather than this being a service of the network itself.
** [[CSNET|Computer Science Network]] (CSNET) &ndash; a computer network created in the United States for computer science departments at academic and research institutions that could not be directly connected to ARPANET, due to funding or authorization limitations. It played a significant role in spreading awareness of, and access to, national networking and was a major milestone on the path to development of the global Internet.
** [[National Science Foundation Network]] (NSFNET) &ndash; an American networking project, initially created to link researchers to the NSF-funded supercomputing centers that, through further public funding and private industry partnerships, developed into a major part of the early [[Internet backbone]]. 
* History of Internet components
** [[Packet switching#History|History of packet switching]] &ndash; a method of grouping [[Data (computing)|data]] into ''[[Network packet|packets]]'' that are transmitted over a digital [[Telecommunications network|network]], conceived independently by [[Paul Baran]] and [[Donald Davies]] in the early and mid-1960s. 
** [[History of communication protocols]] &ndash; the set of rules to enable [[data communication]] between computers on a network. 
** [[Internetworking#History|History of internetworking]] &ndash; networking between computers on different networks. 
** [[VBNS|very high speed Backbone Network Service]] (vBNS) &ndash; 
** [[Network access point]] (NAP) &ndash; 
** [[Federal Internet Exchange]] (FIX) &ndash; 
** [[Commercial Internet eXchange]] (CIX) &ndash;
* [[List of Internet pioneers]]
* [[Timeline of Internet conflicts]]

