==Web index==
{{Main|Web Index}}

The Web index is a composite statistic designed and produced by the [[World Wide Web Foundation]]. It provides a multi-dimensional measure of the [[World Wide Web]]'s contribution to development and human rights globally.  It covers 86 countries as of 2014, the latest year for which the index has been compiled.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://thewebindex.org/data/?indicator=INDEX&country=ALL |publisher=[[World Wide Web Foundation]] |title=Web Index 2014 data |access-date=5 April 2017 |archive-date=16 May 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200516045758/https://thewebindex.org/data/?indicator=INDEX&country=ALL |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://thewebindex.org/blog/web-index-taking-a-break-in-2015/ |title=Web Index – taking a break in 2015 |publisher=[[World Wide Web Foundation]] |date=24 November 2014 |access-date=5 April 2017 |archive-date=18 March 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170318080218/http://thewebindex.org/blog/web-index-taking-a-break-in-2015/ |url-status=live }}</ref> It incorporates [[Economic indicator|indicators]] that assess the areas of [[universal design|universal access]], freedom and openness, relevant content, and empowerment, which indicate economic, social, and political impacts of the Web.

[[File:World Map of Web Index 2014.svg |thumb|left |600px |Map showing the score of the countries included in the Web index.]]
