{{term|term=[[Amphoterism]]|content='''[[Amphoterism]]'''}}{{defn|defn=In chemistry, an ''amphoteric'' compound is a molecule or ion that can react both as an [[acid]] as well as a [[base (chemistry)|base]].<ref>{{GoldBookRef |title=amphoteric |file=A00306}}</ref> Many metals (such as [[copper]], [[zinc]], [[tin]], [[lead]], [[aluminium]], and [[beryllium]]) form amphoteric oxides or hydroxides. Amphoterism depends on the [[oxidation states]] of the oxide. Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> is an example of an amphoteric oxide.}}
