{{term|term=[[Beer–Lambert law]]|content='''[[Beer–Lambert law]]'''}}{{defn|defn=The ''Beer–Lambert law'', also known as ''Beer's law'', the ''Lambert–Beer law'', or the ''Beer–Lambert–Bouguer law'' relates the [[absorption (electromagnetic radiation)|attenuation]] of [[light]] to the properties of the material through which the light is travelling. The law is commonly applied to [[chemical analysis]] measurements and used in understanding attenuation in [[physical optics]], for [[photon]]s, [[neutron]]s, or rarefied gases. In [[mathematical physics]], this law arises as a solution of the [[Bhatnagar–Gross–Krook|BGK equation]].}}
