{{term|term=[[Coulomb]]|content='''[[Coulomb]]'''}}{{defn|defn=The ''coulomb'' (symbol: C) is the [[International System of Units]] (SI) unit of [[electric charge]]. It is the charge (symbol: ''Q'' or ''q'') transported by a constant current of one [[ampere]] in one [[second]]:
: <math>1 ~ \text{C}=1 ~ \text{A} \cdot 1 ~ \text{s}</math>
Thus, it is also the amount of excess charge on a [[capacitor]] of one [[farad]] charged to a potential difference of one [[volt]]:
: <math>1 ~ \text{C}=1 ~ \text{F} \cdot 1 ~ \text{V}</math>
The coulomb is equivalent to the charge of approximately {{val|6.242|e=18}} ({{val|1.036|e=-5}} [[mole (unit)|mol]]) [[proton]]s, and −1&nbsp;C is equivalent to the charge of approximately {{val|6.242|e=18}} [[electron]]s.

A [[2019 revision of the SI|new definition]], in terms of the [[elementary charge]], will take effect on 20 May 2019.<ref name=draft-resolution-A>{{citation
|title=Draft Resolution A "On the revision of the International System of units (SI)" to be submitted to the CGPM at its 26th meeting in November 2018.
|url=https://www.bipm.org/utils/en/pdf/CGPM/Draft-Resolution-A-EN.pdf
|access-date=2019-01-05
|archive-date=2018-04-29
|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180429025229/https://www.bipm.org/utils/en/pdf/CGPM/Draft-Resolution-A-EN.pdf
}}</ref>
The new definition defines the [[elementary charge]] (the charge of the proton) as exactly {{val|1.602176634|e=-19}} coulombs. This would implicitly define the coulomb as {{frac|{{val|0.1602176634}}}}{{e|18}} elementary charges.}}
{{term|term=[[Coulomb's law]]|content='''[[Coulomb's law]]'''}}{{defn|defn=''Coulomb's law'', or ''Coulomb's inverse-square law'', is a [[physical law|law]] of [[physics]] for quantifying Coulomb's force, or electrostatic force. Electrostatic force is the amount of force with which stationary, [[electric charge|electrically charged]] particles either repel, or attract each other. This force and the law for quantifying it, represent one of the most basic forms of force used in the physical sciences, and were an essential basis to the study and development of the theory and field of [[classical electromagnetism]]. The law was first published in 1785 by French physicist [[Charles-Augustin de Coulomb]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reference.com/science/electrostatic-force-explained-e59fd6cfe9ce6a6 |title=How is electrostatic force explained? |website=Reference* |year=2019 |publisher=IAC Publishing, LLC |access-date=January 5, 2019}}</ref>

In its [[scalar (physics)|scalar]] form, the law is:
: <math>F=k_e\frac{q_1 q_2}{r^2}</math>,

where ''k''{{sub|''e''}} is the [[Coulomb constant]] (''k''{{sub|''e''}} ≈ {{val|9e9|u=N⋅m{{sup|2}}⋅C{{sup|−2}}}}), ''q''{{sub|1}} and ''q''{{sub|2}} are the signed magnitudes of the charges, and the scalar ''r'' is the distance between the charges. The force of the interaction between the charges is attractive if the charges have opposite signs (i.e., ''F'' is negative) and repulsive if like-signed (i.e., ''F'' is positive).

Being an [[inverse-square law]], the law is analogous to [[Isaac Newton]]'s inverse-square [[Newton's law of universal gravitation|law of universal gravitation]]. Coulomb's law can be used to derive [[Gauss's law]], and vice versa.}}
{{term|term=[[Covalent bond]]|content='''[[Covalent bond]]'''}}{{defn|defn=A ''covalent bond'', also called a ''molecular bond'', is a [[chemical bond]] that involves the sharing of [[electron pair]]s between [[atom]]s.}}
