'''Overprovisioning''' is the technique of committing more of some resource than strictly necessary, in order to improve the performance or reliability of an engineered system. In specific contexts, overprovisioning can describe:

==Network engineering==
Computer networks can be designed to allocate additional bandwidth in {{section link|Network planning and design|Dimensioning}}.

==Computer data storage==
[[Computer data storage|Storage devices]] may contain more physical storage space than their advertised capacity, reserving the additional capacity to improve the device's performance or endurance characteristics.<ref>{{cite web |author1-link=Storage Networking Industry Association |title=over provisioning |url=https://www.snia.org/education/online-dictionary/term/over-provisioning |website=SNIA Dictionary |publisher=Storage Networking Industry Association |access-date=8 November 2024}}</ref> For example, [[solid-state drive]]s allocate a reserve for [[wear leveling]] to mitigate [[write amplification]].

