{{term|term='''[[Phase (matter)]]'''}}{{defn|defn=In the [[physical sciences]], a phase is a region of space (a [[thermodynamic system]]), throughout which all physical properties of a material are essentially uniform.<ref>{{cite book|last=Modell|first=Michael|author2=Robert C. Reid|title=Thermodynamics and Its Applications|publisher=Prentice-Hall|location=Englewood Cliffs, NJ|date=1974|isbn=978-0-13-914861-3|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/thermodynamicsit00mode}}</ref><ref name="Fermi2012">{{cite book|author=Enrico Fermi|title=Thermodynamics|date=25 April 2012|publisher=Courier Corporation|isbn=978-0-486-13485-7}}</ref>{{rp|86}}<ref name="Adkins1983">{{cite book|author=Clement John Adkins|title=Equilibrium Thermodynamics|date=14 July 1983|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-27456-2}}</ref>{{rp|3}} Examples of physical properties include [[density]], [[index of refraction]], [[magnetization]] and chemical composition. A simple description is that a phase is a region of material that is chemically uniform, physically distinct, and (often) mechanically separable. In a system consisting of ice and water in a glass jar, the ice cubes are one phase, the water is a second phase, and the humid air is a third phase over the ice and water. The glass of the jar is another separate phase. (See {{section link|state of matter|Glass}})}}
{{term|term='''[[Phase (waves)]]'''}}{{defn|defn=In [[physics]] and [[mathematics]], the phase of a [[periodic function]] <math>F</math> of some [[real number|real]] variable <math>t</math> (such as time) is an [[angle]]-like quantity representing the fraction of the cycle covered up to <math>t</math>.  It is denoted <math>\phi(t)</math> and expressed in such a [[scale (ratio)|scale]] that it varies by one full [[turn (geometry)|turn]] as the variable <math>t</math> goes through each [[Period (physics)|period]] (and <math>F(t)</math> goes through each complete cycle).  It may be [[Measure (mathematics)|measured]] in any [[angular unit]] such as [[degree (angle)|degrees]] or [[radians]], thus increasing by 360° or <math>2\pi</math> as the variable <math>t</math> completes a full period.<ref name=Ballou2005>{{cite book |last=Ballou |first=Glen |title=Handbook for sound engineers |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=y0d9VA0lkogC&pg=PA1499 |edition=3 |year=2005 |publisher=Focal Press, Gulf Professional Publishing |isbn=978-0-240-80758-4 |page=1499}}</ref>}}
{{term|term='''[[Phase diagram]]'''}}{{defn|defn=A phase diagram in [[physical chemistry]], [[engineering]], [[mineralogy]], and [[materials science]] is a type of [[chart]] used to show conditions (pressure, temperature, volume, etc.) at which thermodynamically distinct [[phase (matter)|phases]] (such as solid, liquid or gaseous states) occur and coexist at [[thermodynamic equilibrium|equilibrium]].}} 
{{term|term='''[[Phase rule]]'''}}{{defn|defn=In [[thermodynamics]], the phase rule is a general principle governing "pVT" systems (that is, systems whose [[Thermodynamic state|states]] are completely described by the variables [[pressure]] ({{mvar|p}}), [[volume]] ({{mvar|V}}) and [[temperature]] ({{mvar|T}})) in [[thermodynamic equilibrium]]. If {{mvar|F}} is the number of [[Degrees of freedom (physics and chemistry)|degrees of freedom]], {{mvar|C}} is the number of [[Component (thermodynamics)|components]] and {{mvar|P}} is the number of [[Phase (matter)|phases]], then<ref>{{Cite book|last=Smith|first=Joe Mauk|title=Introduction to chemical engineering thermodynamics|publisher=McGraw-Hill Education|year=2018|isbn=978-1-259-69652-7|location=United States of America|pages=422}}</ref><ref name="Atkins">{{cite book |last1=Atkins |first1=Peter |last2=Paula |first2=Julio De |last3=Keeler |first3=James |title=Atkins' Physical chemistry |date=2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |isbn=9780198769866 |pages=123&ndash;125 |edition=Eleventh}}</ref> 
: <math>F = C - P + 2.</math>
It was derived by American physicist [[Josiah Willard Gibbs]] in his landmark paper titled ''[[On the Equilibrium of Heterogeneous Substances]]'', published in parts between 1875 and 1878.<ref>{{citation|first=J. W.|last=Gibbs|author-link=Josiah Willard Gibbs|title=Scientific Papers |location=Dover, New York|year=1961}}</ref>
The rule assumes the components do not [[Chemical reaction|react]] with each other.}}
{{term|term='''[[Photon]]'''}}{{defn|defn=is a type of [[elementary particle]]. It is the [[quantum]] of the [[electromagnetic field]] including [[electromagnetic radiation]] such as [[light]] and [[radio wave]]s, and the [[force carrier]] for the [[electromagnetic force]]. Photons are [[massless]],{{efn|The photon's [[invariant mass]] (also called "rest mass" for massive particles) is believed to be exactly zero.  This is the notion of particle mass generally used by modern physicists.  The photon does have a nonzero [[relativistic mass]], depending on its energy, but this varies according to the [[frame of reference]].}} so they always move at the [[speed of light in vacuum]], {{val|299792458|u=m/s}} (or about {{convert|299792458|m/s|mi/s|disp=out|sigfig=6}}). The photon belongs to the class of [[bosons]].}}
