{{term|term='''[[Watt]]'''}}{{defn|defn=The SI unit of power, rate of doing work.}}  
{{term|term='''[[Wave]]'''}}{{defn|defn=is a disturbance that transfers [[energy]] through [[matter]] or space, with little or no associated [[mass]] transport. Waves consist of [[oscillation]]s or [[vibration]]s of a physical [[Transmission medium|medium]] or a [[field (physics)|field]], around relatively fixed locations. From the perspective of mathematics, waves, as functions of time and space, are a class of [[signal]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Chakravorty |first1=Pragnan |title=What Is a Signal? [Lecture Notes] |journal=IEEE Signal Processing Magazine |date=September 2018 |volume=35 |issue=5 |pages=175–177 |doi=10.1109/MSP.2018.2832195 |bibcode=2018ISPM...35e.175C }}</ref>}} 
{{term|term='''[[Wavelength]]'''}}{{defn|defn=is the ''spatial period'' of a periodic wave—the distance over which the wave's shape repeats.<ref name=hecht>
