== X-Z ==
{{Anchor|X}}{{glossary}}
{{term|term='''[[X-axis]]'''}}{{defn|defn=in algebraic geometry, the axis on a [[Graph of a function|graph]] that is usually drawn left to right and usually shows the range of values of an [[independent variable]].<ref>[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/x-axis Wiktionary]</ref>}}
{{anchor|Y}}{{term|term='''[[Y-axis]]'''}}{{defn|defn=in algebraic geometry, the axis on a [[Graph of a function|graph]] that is usually drawn from bottom to top and usually shows the range of values of [[variable (mathematics)|variable]] dependent on one other variable, or the second of two [[independent variable]]s.<ref>[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/y-axis Wiktionary]</ref>}} 
{{term|term='''[[Yield (engineering)|Yield]]'''}}{{defn|defn=The point of maximum elastic deformation of a material; above yield the material is permanently deformed.}} 
{{term|term='''[[Young's modulus]]'''}}{{defn|defn=A measure of the stiffness of a material; the amount of force per unit area require to produce a unit strain.}} 
{{anchor|Z}}{{term|term='''[[Z-axis]]'''}}{{defn|defn=In algebraic geometry, the axis on a [[Graph of a function|graph]] of at least three [[dimension]]s that is usually drawn vertically and usually shows the range of values of a [[variable (mathematics)|variable]] dependent on two other variables or the third independent variable.<ref>[https://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/z-axis Wiktionary]</ref>}}
{{term|term='''[[Zero defects]]'''}}{{defn|defn=A quality assurance philosophy that aims to reduce the need for inspection of components by improving their quality.}}
{{term|term='''[[Zero force member]]'''}}{{defn|defn=In the field of [[engineering mechanics]], a ''zero force member'' is a member (a single truss segment) in a [[truss]] which, given a specific [[structural load|load]], is at rest: neither in [[tension (mechanics)|tension]], nor in [[compression (physical)|compression]]. In a truss a zero force member is often found at pins (any connections within the truss) where no external load is applied and three or fewer truss members meet. Recognizing basic zero force members can be accomplished by analyzing the [[force]]s acting on an individual pin in a physical [[system]].

''Note: If the pin has an external force or [[Moment (physics)|moment]] applied to it, then all of the members attached to that pin are not zero force members ''unless'' the external force acts in a manner that fulfills one of the rules below:''
* If two non-collinear members meet in an unloaded [[Joint (building)|joint]], both are zero-force members.
* If three members meet in an unloaded joint of which two are collinear, then the third member is a zero-force member.

''Reasons for zero-force members in a truss system''
* These members contribute to the stability of the structure, by providing buckling prevention for long slender members under compressive forces
* These members can carry loads in the event that variations are introduced in the normal external loading configuration.}}
{{term|term='''[[Zeroth law of thermodynamics]]'''}}{{defn|defn=The equivalence principle applied to temperature; two systems in thermal equilibrium with a third are also in thermal equilibrium with each other.}}
